The MAGA vibe shift has come for public institutions, and museums are emerg=
ing
as the next target. Will the mood truly impact the way identity art is valu=
ed in the culture? Or has the market already moved on?

Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

It=E2=80=99s been a tough couple of weeks in Washington. The various attack=
s on the
way D.C. operates=E2=80=94thrilling to some, horrifying to others=E2=80=94h=
ave made President Trump=E2=80=99s decision to replace the board of the Ken=
nedy Center with loyalists, and anoint himself as chair, seem more like com=
ic relief than a consequential move. After all, the role, which billionaire=
 Carlyle Group co-founder David Rubenstein held for more than a decade, req=
uires deep pockets and generosity. Trump may or may not have the former, bu=
t he definitely isn=E2=80=99t known for the
latter.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Last year, the federal government provided only $45 million to the Kennedy =
Center, or less than 17 percent of its total funding. Another $95 million, =
or more than 35 percent of the budget, came from donations. That=E2=80=99s =
an amount Rubenstein, a relentless schmoozer and networker, could easily ra=
ise. But I don=E2=80=99t think anyone imagines that Donald Trump, in or out=
 of office, would be willing to do
the same for this institution. And it=E2=80=99s not conceivable to think he=
 would reach into his own pockets to make up the shortfall.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At first, the move seemed like just another pandering swipe at =E2=80=9Celi=
tes=E2=80=9D from a man who had The Village People perform at his inaugural=
=2E There=E2=80=99s no evidence that, give=
n the choice, Trump would sit throu=
gh any of the performances offered at the Kennedy Center. Even the fact
that the board firings were uncontested suggested that the =E2=80=9Ctakeove=
r=E2=80=9D was only a stunt, until some fascinating context involving Trump=
=E2=80=99s first press secretary, Sean Spicer, was revealed ( https://www.w=
ashingtonpost.com/entertainment/2025/02/14/trump-kennedy-center-sean-spicer=
-lawsuit/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_con=
tent=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action=
&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) in The Washington=
 Post on Friday.

Indeed, not long into the Biden administration, Spicer and top Trump
advisor Stephen Miller launched a pyrrhic lawsuit over Spicer=E2=80=99s fir=
ing from the Naval Academy =E2=80=9Cboard of visitors,=E2=80=9D a case that=
 ended up explicitly defining the sitting president=E2=80=99s right to dism=
iss and appoint members of boards like the one for the Kennedy Center. One =
might have left the whole episode there had the museum world not already be=
gun worrying about the president=E2=80=99s fatwa against D.E.I. initiatives=
, which have become museum orthodoxy in recent years. How exposed
are they to the loss of federal grants or to further interference? And what=
, exactly, does it mean that the Trump administration considers ( https://w=
ww.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/01/ending-radical-and-wasteful-=
government-dei-programs-and-preferencing/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2=
F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a ) D.E.I. programming to be =E2=80=9Cillegal=E2=80=9D?=C2=A0

Almost a year ago, MoMA director Glenn Lowry predicted that museums, like e=
lite
universities before them, would become a ripe target for populists in gover=
nment positions. We=E2=80=99ve already discussed the fabricated scandal at =
the Fort Worth Modern, where an activist website funded by Trump allies man=
ufactured an outcry that prompted county officials to impound photographs b=
y Sally Mann from a museum exhibition and threaten to launch a criminal inv=
estigation with curators as the targets. Given that federal power is vastly=
 greater than that of any county
government, many are fearful of how the Lowry thesis might manifest itself =
now.

The Lowry Thesis
----------------

The Post=E2=80=99s Philip Kennicott began the week by
speculating ( https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/2025/02/10/trump=
-plan-for-arts-humanities/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F1=
6%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medi=
um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) =
on worst-case scenarios whose effects could spread far beyond the Kennedy C=
enter. He pointed out that J.D. Vance has previously attacked the Ford Foun=
dation in the name of combatting D.E.I. by threatening to raise taxes on th=
eir endowment. (During his Senate campaign, Vance went so far as to argue t=
he government should
=E2=80=9Cseize their assets.=E2=80=9D) Would Trump also go after the tax in=
centives that encourage rich people to donate art to museums? What about th=
e Arts & Artifacts Indemnity Program, which reduces the prohibitive cost of=
 insuring treasured works coming to the United States for blockbuster museu=
m shows? Suddenly, these are no longer absurd prospects.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Picking up on this theme, The Art Newspaper
asked ( https://www.theartnewspaper.com/2025/02/14/as-americas-wealthiest-l=
urch-to-the-right-will-high-value-art?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBE=
RS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%=
29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da=
42abd12a ) on Friday whether, =E2=80=9Cas the wealthiest lurch to the right=
, will the commercial art world follow?=E2=80=9D But the story largely fail=
ed to make the case that the art market has begun to parrot MAGA talking po=
ints. Many of Trump=E2=80=99s richest supporters have been all too happy to=
 buy art with some sort of identity element. Even
Stephen Schwarzman, who threw in with Trump and has kept busy decorating er=
satz ancestral homes in the U.S. and the U.K., has bought relatively obscur=
e female abstract expressionist painters, his art advisor told me last year=
=2E Indeed, who does The Art Newspaper=20=
think was buying all of those non-whit=
e, non-male artists? It wasn=E2=80=99t solely wealthy progressives.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Of course, no
discussion of a repudiation of identity art would be complete without menti=
oning Dean Kissick=E2=80=99s much-discussed Harper=E2=80=99s essay ( https:=
//harpers.org/archive/2024/12/the-painted-protest-dean-kissick-contemporary=
-art/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_content=
=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm=
_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) from December, =E2=80=
=9CThe Painted Protest.=E2=80=9D Like Tom Wolfe did in his famous 1976 =E2=
=80=9CMe Decade=E2=80=9D essay in New York magazine, Kissick strings togeth=
er some trenchant cultural
observations with a few unrelated sensationalistic scenes, such as the luri=
d opener in which his mother is run over by a bus on her way to see an exhi=
bition at London=E2=80=99s Barbican, which resulted in the loss of her legs=
=2E In the piece, Kissick has her ask,=
 improbably, whether the show about =E2=
=80=9Cpower and politics in textile art=E2=80=9D was worth the price.=C2=A0

No exhibition, obviously, whether organized around hothouse political claim=
s or featuring ineffable
art, is worth losing limbs over. And the anecdote=E2=80=94and several other=
 jejune comparisons and observations=E2=80=94almost obscures the valuable p=
oints that Kissick has to make. Indeed, the essay toggles between tendentio=
us cheap shots and brilliant observations. But his main point=E2=80=94the n=
otion that fixating on the identity of an artist is a lousy way to determin=
e whether their art is any good=E2=80=94is anything but controversial. For =
all of its complaining, Kissick=E2=80=99s essay isn=E2=80=99t concerned wit=
h art itself, but with
an exhaustion about the way we talk about the artists. (He thinks that has =
resulted in boring art.)

A few weeks ago, in a conversation with a prospective client, a Black deale=
r mocked the catch-all term identity artists to refer to the wide range of =
talents who have become prominent on the market since 2018. The dealer was =
understandably fed up with language that reduced artists, including many he=
 represents, to
categories and identities; he was just as tired of the emphasis as many of =
the MAGA types that the industry fears. But looking over the mid-season sal=
es catalogs this weekend, there was no overt emphasis on the identity of th=
e individual artists, even though there are many artists who are not white =
men present in the catalogs. And that=E2=80=99s why I=E2=80=99m not that wo=
rried about the art market=E2=80=99s ability to withstand the MAGA onslaugh=
t.=C2=A0

Museums are another story. We=E2=80=99re only
now seeing the debuts of many shows conceived in the wake of George Floyd=
=E2=80=99s 2020 murder, and there are surely more to come. Some of these sh=
ows will be powerful and great; others, meanwhile=E2=80=94like The Met=E2=
=80=99s Flight Into Egypt: Black Artists and Ancient Egypt=E2=80=94will be =
try-hard, and leave themselves open to attack. That means we=E2=80=99re lik=
ely to see more examples of MAGA enthusiasts picking fights with museums. B=
ut whatever the mood of our culture and politics, the market will
continue to seek out new talents, not as categories but as artists. Some wi=
ll have a brief moment in the sun. Others will become lasting figures in ou=
r culture. There=E2=80=99s no dictating taste.

=E2=80=8A

