a ), late on Friday, that the late Barnes & Noble founder Len Riggio=E2=80=
=99s estate was the subject of bidding between the auction houses. The folk=
s there were trying to figure out what works might be included in the packa=
ge and whether terms and guarantees would be worked out in time for the May=
 sales. (Why else would the
estate be engaged in discussions now?) Of course, it=E2=80=99s my understan=
ding that, after a couple of weeks of outside-the-box presentations, the de=
al is now done. Though, it doesn=E2=80=99t sound like we=E2=80=99re going t=
o see all of Riggio=E2=80=99s art come to the block. Most likely, the estat=
e is only selling enough to cover taxes.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Over at Artnet, the anonymous art dealer writing letters to clients and art=
ists and
now ( https://news.artnet.com/art-world-archives/dear-art-advisors-advice-2=
603770?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F16%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) art advisors has bet=
rayed a lack of understanding about what it means to be in sales. At the en=
d of a five-point rant, she tells advisors that they should not rely on a g=
allery director for things like shipping costs and sales tax. Then, unable =
to hold it in any longer, she shouts, =E2=80=9CYou=E2=80=99re an adult bein=
g paid an adult commission: Do your job!=E2=80=9D But, of
course, anyone who is in sales will tell you that it=E2=80=99s their job to=
 do whatever it takes to make the sale happen.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s enough for today. More from the road this coming week.

=C2=A0

Until then,

M

